<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1256,1282]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The only 
<taxonomicName box="[438,550,1256,1282]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[438,550,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Haliclona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Eastern Pacific with a combination of smooth surface, rare oscula, blue colour alive, and an irregular anisotropic reticulation with loose uni- to paucispicular primary tracts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,473,1328,1354]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
Description (
<figureCitation box="[354,460,1328,1354]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-18@36.[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 12. Haliclona (Rhizoniera) baslaviae sp. nov. (MNRJ 12856, holotype). A, holotype alive; B, skeletal architecture in transverse ground section; C–D, oxeas. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 500 μm; C–D, 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824049/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Fig. 12A</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Small specimen, ca. 
<quantity box="[716,772,1328,1355]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
in largest diameter, thickly encrusting on an empty limpet shell. Surface smooth. Oscula rare, circular, 
<quantity box="[648,713,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Consistency soft. Colour purplish blue in life.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,433,1400,1426]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
Skeleton (
<figureCitation box="[316,420,1400,1426]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-18@36.[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 12. Haliclona (Rhizoniera) baslaviae sp. nov. (MNRJ 12856, holotype). A, holotype alive; B, skeletal architecture in transverse ground section; C–D, oxeas. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 500 μm; C–D, 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824049/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Fig. 12B</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Ectosome not specialized. Choanosome an irregular anisotropic reticulation, loose uni- to paucispicular primary tracts connected by unispicular secondary tracts. Few pauci- to multispicular discontinuous tracts, perpendicular to the surface, deep in the choanosome. Choanosomal and subectosomal spaces present, 150– 780 µm in diameter. Many free spicules around. Spongin not visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,463,1544,1570]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
Spicules (
<figureCitation box="[311,448,1544,1570]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-18@36.[181,1405,181,1909]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 12. Haliclona (Rhizoniera) baslaviae sp. nov. (MNRJ 12856, holotype). A, holotype alive; B, skeletal architecture in transverse ground section; C–D, oxeas. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, 500 μm; C–D, 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824049/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Fig. 12C, D</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Oxeas, slender, subtly bent at centre, long acerate points, dimensions 133– 
<emphasis box="[1294,1336,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">151</emphasis>
–169 µm x 4.0– 
<emphasis box="[221,256,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">5.3</emphasis>
–6.0 µm (n = 20 x 10).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1305,1616,1643]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" box="[199,1305,1616,1643]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1616,1642]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Ecology.</emphasis>
Shallow subtidal, markedly silted habitat. Water temperature during collection was 21°C.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1271,1652,1679]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" box="[199,1271,1652,1679]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,464,1652,1678]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[360,449,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1807,1831]" captionTargetBox="[159,1429,563,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-185@7.[155,1432,561,1783]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Map showing the geographic distribution of Peruvian haplosclerids. A, distribution of Chalinula chelysa sp. nov.; B, distribution of Chalinula ramiculosa sp. nov. and Haliclona (G.) concreta sp nov.; C, distribution of H. (Halich.) arequipaensis sp. nov., H. (Halich.) multiosculata sp. nov. and H. (Halich.) marcoriosi sp. nov.; D, distribution of H. (Halich.) paracas sp. nov., H. (Halich.) pellucida sp. nov. and (Reniera) parvuloxea sp. nov.; E, distribution of H. (Rhizoniera) spp. nov.; F, distribution of Niphates ruthecitae sp. nov. and Pachychalina lupusapia sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824023" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824023/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Only known from its 
<typeStatus box="[712,760,1653,1679]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">type</typeStatus>
locality at Laguna Grande (Paracas), in 
<collectingCountry box="[1212,1267,1653,1679]" name="Peru" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Peru</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1688,1714]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet honours Dr. Báslavi Cóndor-Luján who, as an undergraduate, participated in our fieldwork year after year, and followed up developing her career in sponge taxonomy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="238" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1760,1786]" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Remarks.</emphasis>
The anisotropic, ladder-like reticulation of the new species is similar to that found in 
<emphasis box="[1272,1299,1761,1786]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1315,1427,1760,1786]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1315,1427,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Haliclona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<emphasis box="[197,225,1797,1822]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[239,362,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Rhizoniera</emphasis>
). However, the reticulation in 
<emphasis box="[697,724,1797,1822]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName box="[739,851,1796,1822]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[739,851,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Haliclona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is supposed to be very regular, with straight primary lines, while in the new species it is more irregular with spongin not observable. Thus, 
<emphasis box="[1131,1159,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1176,1299,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Rhizoniera</emphasis>
) remains as the best assignment for the new species, especially after the amendment of the subgeneric diagnosis by 
<bibRefCitation author="Muricy, G. &amp; Esteves, E. L. &amp; Monteiro, L. C. &amp; Rodrigues, B. R. &amp; Albano, R. M." pageId="35" pageNumber="236" pagination="536 - 550" refId="ref37338" refString="Muricy, G., Esteves, E. L., Monteiro, L. C., Rodrigues, B. R. &amp; Albano, R. M. (2015) A new species of Haliclona (Demospongiae: Haplosclerida: Chalinidae) from Southeastern Brazil and the first record of Haliclona vansoesti from the Brazilian coast. Zootaxa, 3925 (4), 536 - 550. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3925.4.3" type="journal article" year="2015">
Muricy 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
to allow the inclusion of species with unispicular primary lines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1148,2039]" lastBlockId="37.[151,1437,151,681]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="238" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">
This is the only blue 
<taxonomicName box="[441,553,1940,1966]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[441,553,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Haliclona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
found in 
<collectingCountry box="[665,720,1941,1967]" name="Peru" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Peru</collectingCountry>
. Other congeners in the Eastern Pacific showing similar colour when alive are 
<emphasis box="[329,356,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[374,458,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Halich.</emphasis>
) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thinly" baseAuthorityName="de Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[476,579,1976,2002]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gellindra">
<emphasis box="[476,579,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">gellindra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[595,623,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[641,725,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Halich.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[743,813,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">thielei</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cushion" baseAuthorityName="Thiele" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[829,1020,1976,2003]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="topsenti" subGenus="Re.">
<emphasis box="[829,857,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[875,912,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Re.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[931,1020,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">topsenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<emphasis box="[1085,1113,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1131,1209,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Halicl.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1227,1339,1977,2002]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">verrucosa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thiele, J." pageId="35" pageNumber="236" pagination="407 - 496" refId="ref38628" refString="Thiele, J. (1905) Die Kiesel- und Hornschwamme der Sammlung Plate. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Supplement 6 (Fauna Chilensis III), 407 - 496." type="journal article" year="1905">Thiele, 1905</bibRefCitation>
) (
<tableCitation box="[232,320,2012,2038]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,239,504,530]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 3. Comparative data on external morphology, anatomy, spicule length x width, and known distribution for Chalinula spp., Haliclona spp. Niphates spp. and Pachychalina spp. occurring along the Eastern Pacific and in transitional areas between the Pacific and Atlantic (Beagle Channel and Strait of Magellan). (Ecto. = ectosome; Choano. = choanosome). Sources: Wilson (1904); Thiele (1905); de Laubenfels (1926, 1930, 1932); Dickinson (1945); Sarà (1978); Desqueyroux-Faúndez (1990); Desqueyroux-Faúndez &amp; van Soest (1997); Gómez et al. (2002); Cruz-Barraza &amp; Carballo (2006, 2008); van Soest (2017); Gastaldi et al. (2018); Sim-Smith et al. (2021); present study." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/D6C6E2D529570D427DC7FE306B77FDF1" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" tableUuid="D6C6E2D529570D427DC7FE306B77FDF1">Table 3</tableCitation>
). The new species can be promptly set apart from 
<emphasis box="[899,926,2013,2038]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[943,1027,2012,2038]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">Halich.</emphasis>
) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thinly" baseAuthorityName="de Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1044,1147,2012,2038]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="35" pageNumber="236" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gellindra">
<emphasis box="[1044,1147,2012,2038]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="236">gellindra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the presence of a tangential ectosome and a dense, confused, subisotropic choanosomal skeleton (
<bibRefCitation author="de Laubenfels, M. W." box="[1081,1309,151,177]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" pagination="1 - 140" refId="ref35428" refString="de Laubenfels, M. W. (1932) The marine and fresh-water sponges of California. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 81 (2927), 1 - 140. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.81 - 2927.1" type="journal article" year="1932">de Laubenfels 1932</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="de Weerdt, W. H." pageId="37" pageNumber="238" pagination="852 - 873" refId="ref35823" refString="de Weerdt, W. H. (2002) Family Chalinidae Gray, 1867. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera: A Guide to the Classification of Sponges. Springer US, Boston, Massachusetts, pp. 852 - 873. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 91" type="book chapter" year="2002">de Weerdt 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The “spicule reinforced form” of 
<emphasis box="[607,635,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[651,735,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">Halich.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[751,821,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">thielei</emphasis>
has an encrusting habit, 
<quantity box="[1100,1194,187,213]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3 mm</quantity>
thick, and blue green or violet-grey colour, similarly to 
<taxonomicName authority="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu, 2022" authorityName="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2022" box="[528,732,223,249]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="baslaviae" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Rhizoniera">
<emphasis box="[528,556,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[571,610,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">Rh.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[625,732,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">baslaviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[739,828,223,249]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[739,828,223,249]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Even so, both forms of 
<emphasis box="[1095,1123,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1138,1221,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">Halich.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1237,1307,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">thielei</emphasis>
are distinct from 
<taxonomicName authority="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu, 2022" authorityName="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2022" box="[214,422,259,285]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="baslaviae" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Rhizoniera">
<emphasis box="[214,242,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[259,298,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">Rh.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[315,422,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">baslaviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[431,522,259,285]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[431,522,259,285]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The “spicule reinforced form” has a dense and irregular skeleton, and abundant oscula; while the “spongin reinforced form” has a skeleton with abundant nodal spongin, and oscula on top of conical projections up to 
<quantity box="[433,498,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
high (
<bibRefCitation author="Thiele, J." box="[569,709,330,357]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" pagination="407 - 496" refId="ref38628" refString="Thiele, J. (1905) Die Kiesel- und Hornschwamme der Sammlung Plate. Zoologische Jahrbucher, Supplement 6 (Fauna Chilensis III), 407 - 496." type="journal article" year="1905">Thiele 1905</bibRefCitation>
). Both patterns contrast to what is observed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu, 2022" authorityName="Bispo &amp; Willenz &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2022" box="[1231,1436,331,357]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="baslaviae" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Rhizoniera">
<emphasis box="[1231,1259,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1275,1313,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">Rh.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">baslaviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,239,367,393]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,239,367,393]" pageId="37" pageNumber="238" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, that has a mainly unispicular anisotropic architecture, without visible spongin, and seemingly only one, flat oscule. These features clearly set both species apart.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824049" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5824049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824049/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="237" startId="36.[151,250,1933,1957]" targetBox="[181,1405,181,1909]" targetPageId="36">
